## Technical Analysis

### React Masonry CSS Column Spanning

**How It Works:**
React Masonry CSS supports column spanning via className on the item element:

```jsx
<Masonry
  breakpointCols={{ default: 3, 1024: 2, 640: 1 }}
  className="my-masonry-grid"
  columnClassName="my-masonry-grid_column"
>
  {/* 1x width (default) */}
  <div className="widget-card">Widget A</div>

  {/* 2x width - spans 2 columns */}
  <div className="widget-card col-span-2">Widget B</div>

  {/* 3x width - spans 3 columns */}
  <div className="widget-card col-span-3">Widget C</div>
</Masonry>
```

**CSS Implementation:**
```css
.my-masonry-grid {
  display: flex;
  margin-left: -16px; /* gutter size */
}

.my-masonry-grid_column {
  padding-left: 16px;
  background-clip: padding-box;
}

/* Column spanning */
.col-span-2 {
  width: calc(200% + 16px); /* 2 columns + 1 gutter */
}

.col-span-3 {
  width: calc(300% + 32px); /* 3 columns + 2 gutters */
}
```

**Responsive Behavior:**
- Desktop (≥1024px): 3 columns → 1x, 2x, 3x all work
- Tablet (640-1023px): 2 columns → 3x becomes 2x
- Mobile (<640px): 1 column → All become 1x

